        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 33-year-old man in the Czech Republic who works full time in a warehouse logistics role. Over the last several weeks, people close to him have noticed a striking change in his energy and behavior: he has been sleeping only a few hours a night because of persistent insomnia, yet still arrives at work talking rapidly, pacing, and seeming unusually driven and restless with clear psychomotor agitation [SNOMED:F31.9]. During these periods he becomes overly flirtatious and impulsive, with episodes of hypersexual behavior that are very out of character for him [SNOMED:F31.9].\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives alone but stays in close contact with his sister and a small group of friends. He usually enjoys football, video games, and weekend trips, but between elevated phases he can swing into low periods marked by fatigue, hypersomnia, and anhedonia, spending long stretches in bed and losing interest in hobbies and socializing [SNOMED:F31.9]. His coworkers describe him as talented and hardworking when stable, but inconsistent when his mood shifts.\n\nIn more severe high periods, {patientName} has voiced fixed false beliefs that others are watching him and has seemed suspicious and grandiose, consistent with delusional thinking [SNOMED:F31.9]. He has never had a major neurological disorder documented, and his general physical appearance is otherwise unremarkable, but during interview he appears tired around the eyes from poor sleep while simultaneously fidgety and difficult to interrupt because of the current manic symptoms of insomnia and agitation [SNOMED:F31.9].\n\nHe does not describe an especially large social circle, yet his family remains involved because the alternating pattern of mania, hypomania, and depressive symptoms has begun to interfere with relationships and work reliability [SNOMED:F31.9]. He is worried about losing control when symptoms intensify, especially when sleeplessness builds over several nights [SNOMED:F31.9]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:80d1c18c-29e8-407d-bcd6-66fe6ded2fe0",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
