              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports a history of recurrent mood episodes over several years, with periods of elevated mood and reduced sleep suggestive of hypomania or mania, alternating with low periods of fatigue, hypersomnia, and loss of pleasure [SNOMED:F31.9]. He says stress at work tends to worsen his symptoms, and he recalls episodes of anxiety and panic during high-stress periods, which is consistent with one dialogue source describing panic attacks and anxiety around bipolar evaluation [MEDDIALOG:F31.9:0].\n\nHe has not had major chronic medical illness documented. He denies substance injection drug use and has no known history of head trauma. During depressed periods he may withdraw socially and spend most of the day sleeping, while during elevated periods he becomes more impulsive, restless, and socially intrusive with insomnia and psychomotor agitation [SNOMED:F31.9].\n\nThere is no confirmed prior psychiatric hospitalization available in the evidence, but his symptoms have been significant enough to disrupt work and relationships. He has no prior surgeries of relevance and no established neurological diagnosis. He is seeking treatment now because the current episode of poor sleep, agitation, and intermittent grandiose or suspicious ideas has become harder for him to manage, with delusional symptoms reported during severe mood elevation [SNOMED:F31.9]."
          }
        ]
      }
